******
[2]
Date: Mon 21 Mar 2011
Source: Standart News [edited]
<http://paper.standartnews.com/en/article.php?d=2011-03-21&article=35813>


A new outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) has been discovered in
Bulgaria's Burgas district, a day before the European Commission was
expected to lift the measures, imposed on the area because of the
previous FMD cases.

A total of 143 animals will be killed after the virus was discovered
in the tissue of cows during a routine check at a private farm near
the village of Kirovo, close to the border with Turkey. The blood
samples for FMD turned out negative, which means that the
contamination is a week old, according to experts from the Food Safety
Agency.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[If the farm is isolated, surrounded by forest, and the disease is a
week old, it is very persuasive that it might be as a result of nearby
wildlife being infected. If that is so, and it is very speculative, it
will probably delay full restocking. Logically it would begin with a
limited number of sentinel animals. Wild game and farmed game of
species susceptible to FMD in Bulgaria, are addressed in Commission
Decision 2011/44/EU, available at
<http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2011:019:0020:0033:EN:PDF>.
See also 'FMD Makes Mess of Hunting Tourism in Southeast Bulgaria' at
<http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=125217>.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Bulgaria can be seen at
<http://healthmap.org/r/0Bue>. To find Burgas oblast, go to
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/BU/39/> and to find Kirovo, go to
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/BU/39/Kirovo.html>. This is very
close to the Turkish border in SE Bulgaria, and south of Sredets. -
Mod.MHJ]
